{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17491643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17491643"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:56:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1008"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1008"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.03,0.21,0.08,0.08,0.6]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68023"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1008","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1008"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1008"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53488"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"256"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1267"},{"type":"tags","id":"3406"},{"type":"tags","id":"3549"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"9078"},{"type":"tags","id":"9084"},{"type":"tags","id":"9270"},{"type":"tags","id":"9528"},{"type":"tags","id":"9531"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4164"},{"type":"contributions","id":"4165"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43828"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68023","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/68023"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 73-year-old man presents to his general practitioner with a one week history of increasing jaundice. Over the last three months he has lost four kg in weight, which he attributes to a change in his diet. His medical history includes hypertension and type 2 diabetes for which he takes perindopril and metformin. He has recently been on a course of amoxicillin for a chest infection. He has a 30 pack-year smoking history and drinks two glasses of wine a day. Apart from yellow sclera, the physical examination is unremarkable with no abdominal pain. His liver function studies are shown (Image). A CT scan shows a 12 mm diameter common bile duct (normal range 2 - 6 mm) and no other abnormalities.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Review in one month with repeat liver function tests","Right upper quadrant ultrasound","Endoscopic ultrasound","Hepatobiliary iminodiacetic acid (HIDA) scan","Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EJaundice and weight loss in an older patient should always raise the possibility of malignancy. In this case the CT scan has shown a dilated common bile duct and the liver function tests are abnormal, suggesting an underlying obstructive cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMany medications can cause a transient jaundice, amoxycillin being one of the antibiotics that can produce cholestatic drug-induced liver injury (DILI). Whilst uncommon, if this was thought to be the cause of the jaundice a \u003Cstrong\u003Ereview and repeat liver function tests\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate. However, given the weight loss, malignancy must be investigated with DILI a diagnosis of exclusion.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERight upper quadrant ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if the leading differential was gallstone-related disease. The weight loss and absence of pain would not be in keeping with such a diagnosis. A \u003Cstrong\u003EHIDA scan\u003C/strong\u003E provides a functional assessment of the gallbladder, and can be used to provide useful information, such as cystic duct obstruction, if ultrasound is normal.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn patients with presumed malignant biliary tract obstruction, the role of \u003Cstrong\u003Eendoscopic ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E is to get better definition of the presumed lesion and obtain a sample for cytological examination. However, no lesion has been defined on the CT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhilst at some stage, this patient might require endoscopic retrograde cholangiopancreatography (ERCP) to further define the biliary tract, biopsy and possibly stent an obstructing lesion, it is an invasive investigation and does have its complications\u003Cstrong\u003E. Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography\u003C/strong\u003E (MRCP) is non-invasive and will provide more detail about the biliary tree and adjacent structures than an ERCP. In this patient the presumed diagnosis must be a carcinoma of the head of the pancreas - and MRCP has been shown to provide more diagnostic accuracy for small lesions compared with CT.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Magnetic resonance cholangiopancreatography is the preferred imaging modality for obstructive jaundice when no cause has been identified on ultrasound and/or CT"],"references":["Lee ES, Lee JM. Imaging diagnosis of pancreatic cancer: A state-of-the-art review. World J Gastroenterol. 2014; 20(24):7864-77. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24976723/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53488"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1008"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20082"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20082","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20082"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https